body_text.text:
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) is the key cooperation region under the Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) proposed by China.1
China-ASEAN trade increased from US$192.6 billion in 2008 to US$452.2 billion in 2016. In this context of booming trade, China is increasingly sourcing from the region, especially from the Greater Mekong Subregion (GMS) countries. Besides two provinces of China (specifically Yunnan Province and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region2
), GMS includes five countries located in the center of Indo-China Peninsula, namely Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, Myanmar, and Thailand. Cross-border trade has improved significantly in the last years. There is a huge demand in China for tropical fruits, flowers, and other agricultural products from Thailand and Vietnam.
